/-! ### ¬ß10.154 Coefficient-injectivity bridge for `HasFourierSynthesis`

The mathlib Fourier orthonormal basis `mFourierBasis` is a Hilbert basis
on `L¬≤(ūĚēčŠĶą)`; its representation `mFourierBasis.repr` is a continuous
linear equivalence, hence injective.  Via the bridge
`mFourierBasis_repr f m = mFourierCoeff f m` (¬ß10.47-level), this
translates to: two `Lp ‚Ąā 2` elements with matching Fourier coefficients
at every mode are equal.

Using this bridge, the `init_eq` field of `HasFourierSynthesis per őł`
is derivable from the more elementary initial-coefficient match
`per.b m 0 = mFourierCoeff őł m`.  This reduces the `HasFourierSynthesis`
constructor workload (Target #2) from "identify `őł_lim 0` with `őł` at
the `Lp` level" to "match coefficients at `t = 0`" ‚ÄĒ a coefficient-
level check the caller typically has for free from the initial data.

The remaining content of Target #2 (construction of `őł_lim` for
`t > 0` + strong-`L¬≤` convergence of the extracted Galerkin sequence
to `őł_lim`) still requires classical Fourier synthesis + Parseval +
Fatou + dominated convergence on `‚Ąď¬≤(‚Ą§¬≤)`; ¬ß10.154 isolates the
coefficient-injectivity reduction as a reusable building block. -/

/-- **¬ß10.154.A  Lp elements are determined by their Fourier coefficients.**
Two elements of `Lp ‚Ąā 2 (volume : Measure (UnitAddTorus (Fin 2)))` with
matching Fourier coefficients at every mode are equal.  Proof via
injectivity of `mFourierBasis.repr` and the
`mFourierBasis_repr ‚ÜĒ mFourierCoeff` bridge. -/
theorem Lp_eq_of_mFourierCoeff_eq
    (f g : Lp ‚Ąā 2 (volume : Measure (UnitAddTorus (Fin 2))))
    (h : ‚ąÄ m : Fin 2 ‚Üí ‚Ą§, mFourierCoeff f m = mFourierCoeff g m) :
    f = g := by
  apply mFourierBasis.repr.injective
  ext m
  rw [mFourierBasis_repr, mFourierBasis_repr]
  exact h m

/-- **¬ß10.154.B  `HasFourierSynthesis.ofPerModeLimit` constructor.**
Assembles `HasFourierSynthesis per őł` from a synthesis witness `őł_lim`
with `per.b`-matching coefficients at every `t ‚Č• 0`, an initial-
coefficient match `per.b m 0 = mFourierCoeff őł m`, and strong-`L¬≤`
convergence along the extracted subsequence.  The initial-time
equality `őł_lim 0 = őł` is derived internally via ¬ß10.154.A, removing
it from what the caller must supply.

This constructor realises the coefficient-injectivity reduction of
Target #2: the remaining analytical content of `HasFourierSynthesis`
is factored into exactly (i) the synthesis witness `őł_lim` + its
coefficient match, and (ii) strong-`L¬≤` convergence ‚ÄĒ both of which
are the Parseval + dominated-convergence content classically derived
from per-mode convergence + uniform `‚Ąď¬≤` control. -/
noncomputable def HasFourierSynthesis.ofPerModeLimit
    {őĪ : ‚ąÄ n : ‚Ąē, ‚ĄĚ ‚Üí (‚Ü•(sqgBox n) ‚Üí ‚Ąā)}
    (per : HasPerModeLimit őĪ)
    {őł : Lp ‚Ąā 2 (volume : Measure (UnitAddTorus (Fin 2)))}
    (hInit_b : ‚ąÄ m : Fin 2 ‚Üí ‚Ą§, per.b m 0 = mFourierCoeff őł m)
    (őł_lim : ‚ĄĚ ‚Üí Lp ‚Ąā 2 (volume : Measure (UnitAddTorus (Fin 2))))
    (h_coeff : ‚ąÄ (m : Fin 2 ‚Üí ‚Ą§) (t : ‚ĄĚ), 0 ‚Č§ t ‚Üí
      mFourierCoeff (őł_lim t) m = per.b m t)
    (h_L2 : ‚ąÄ (t : ‚ĄĚ), 0 ‚Č§ t ‚Üí
      Filter.Tendsto
        (fun k : ‚Ąē =>
          ‚ąę x, ‚ÄĖgalerkinToLp (sqgBox (per.nsub k)) (őĪ (per.nsub k) t) x
                - őł_lim t x‚ÄĖ ^ 2)
        Filter.atTop (nhds 0)) :
    HasFourierSynthesis per őł where
  őł_lim := őł_lim
  init_eq := by
    apply Lp_eq_of_mFourierCoeff_eq
    intro m
    rw [h_coeff m 0 le_rfl, hInit_b m]
  mFourierCoeff_eq := h_coeff
  tendsto_L2 := h_L2

/-! ### ¬ß10.155 `HasPerModeLimit` from `HasModeLipschitzFamily`
(Arzel√†‚ÄďAscoli + Cantor diagonal reduction)

For each fixed mode `m`, `HasModeLipschitzFamily őĪ` (¬ß10.149) gives the
per-mode sequence `t ‚Ü¶ galerkinExtend (sqgBox n) (őĪ n t) m` which is:

* uniformly bounded by `lip.modeBound t` on forward time;
* uniformly `lip.modeLipschitz m`-Lipschitz on forward time;

hence uniformly equicontinuous on every compact `[0, T]`.  Classical
Arzel√†‚ÄďAscoli applied mode-wise on `[0, T]` + Cantor diagonal across
enumerated modes (`Denumerable (Fin 2 ‚Üí ‚Ą§)`) + truncation `T = 1, 2, ...`
extracts a single subsequence `nsub : ‚Ąē ‚Üí ‚Ąē` with pointwise convergence
at every mode and every `t ‚Č• 0` ‚ÄĒ the output of `HasPerModeLimit`
(¬ß10.150).

¬ß10.155 factors this step into:

* **¬ß10.155.A** `HasModeLipschitzFamily.modeCoeff_eq_galerkinExtend` ‚ÄĒ
  bridge lemma identifying the abstract `lip.modeCoeff` field with the
  concrete `galerkinExtend` form used throughout the chain.
* **¬ß10.155.B** `HasPerModeLimit.ofModeLipschitzFamily` ‚ÄĒ constructor
  that takes a classical Arzel√†‚ÄďAscoli + Cantor diagonal extraction
  witness and produces `HasPerModeLimit őĪ`.

The extraction witness itself (in terms of `galerkinExtend`-shaped
sequences) is the remaining Item 1 Target #1 classical-analysis step;
¬ß10.155.B reduces that step to a single named, precisely-typed
existential hypothesis.  With ¬ß10.152 + ¬ß10.155.B + ¬ß10.154.B + ¬ß10.156,
Item 1's Route B analytical chain is factored into exactly three named
classical theorem signatures (Arzel√†‚ÄďAscoli extraction, Fourier synthesis
existence + L¬≤ convergence, per-mode Lipschitz constant).
-/

/-- **¬ß10.155.A  Bridge lemma: `lip.modeCoeff` = `galerkinExtend` on any
`HasModeLipschitzFamily` instance.**  By the `modeCoeff_eq`/`modeCoeff_off`
fields, `lip.modeCoeff` agrees with the canonical `galerkinExtend` on and
