/-! ### ¬ß11.29 Monotone constant form

For any `C ‚Č• 2^{2s}¬∑(2¬∑latticeZetaConst s)`, the Banach-algebra bound
holds with constant `C`.  Useful for unifying constants across multiple
terms. -/

/-- **¬ß11.29 ‚ÄĒ Monotonicity of the concrete Banach-algebra constant.**
If `C ‚Č• 2^{2s}¬∑(2¬∑latticeZetaConst s)`, then
`HasTrigPolyBanachAlgebraBound s C` holds.  Built from ¬ß11.27 +
monotonicity of the bound structure. -/
theorem hasTrigPolyBanachAlgebraBound_of_gt_one_mono
    {s : ‚ĄĚ} (hs : 1 < s) {C : ‚ĄĚ}
    (hC : 2 ^ (2 * s) * (2 * latticeZetaConst s) ‚Č§ C) :
    HasTrigPolyBanachAlgebraBound s C where
  nonneg := le_trans
    (mul_nonneg (Real.rpow_nonneg (by norm_num : (0 : ‚ĄĚ) ‚Č§ 2) _)
      (mul_nonneg (by norm_num : (0 : ‚ĄĚ) ‚Č§ 2) (latticeZetaConst_nonneg s))) hC
  bound := by
    intros A B cf cg hA hB
    have h := (hasTrigPolyBanachAlgebraBound_of_gt_one hs).bound A B cf cg hA hB
    have h_nnA : 0 ‚Č§ hsSeminormSq s (trigPoly A cf) := hsSeminormSq_nonneg_any _ _
    have h_nnB : 0 ‚Č§ hsSeminormSq s (trigPoly B cg) := hsSeminormSq_nonneg_any _ _
    have h_prod_nn : 0 ‚Č§ hsSeminormSq s (trigPoly A cf) * hsSeminormSq s (trigPoly B cg) :=
      mul_nonneg h_nnA h_nnB
    calc hsSeminormSq s (trigPolyProduct A B cf cg)
        ‚Č§ (2 ^ (2 * s) * (2 * latticeZetaConst s))
            * hsSeminormSq s (trigPoly A cf) * hsSeminormSq s (trigPoly B cg) := h
      _ = (2 ^ (2 * s) * (2 * latticeZetaConst s))
            * (hsSeminormSq s (trigPoly A cf) * hsSeminormSq s (trigPoly B cg)) := by ring
      _ ‚Č§ C * (hsSeminormSq s (trigPoly A cf) * hsSeminormSq s (trigPoly B cg)) :=
          mul_le_mul_of_nonneg_right hC h_prod_nn
      _ = C * hsSeminormSq s (trigPoly A cf) * hsSeminormSq s (trigPoly B cg) := by ring

/-! ### ¬ß12 Distributional weak form ‚üļ mode-wise Duhamel identity

This section addresses the model-correctness concern flagged in the
2026-04-22 memo: the repo's `IsSqgWeakSolution` carries the mode-wise
Duhamel identity as its defining field, whereas the classical notion
of "weak solution of the SQG equation `‚ąā_t őł + u ¬∑ ‚ąáőł = 0` on
`ūĚēč¬≤ √ó [0, T]`" is the distributional identity

  `‚ąę‚āÄ^T ‚ü®őł(ŌĄ), ‚ąā_ŌĄ ŌÜ(¬∑, ŌĄ)‚ü©_{L¬≤(ūĚēč¬≤)} dŌĄ`
  `  + ‚ąę‚āÄ^T ‚ü®őł(ŌĄ)¬∑u(ŌĄ), ‚ąá_x ŌÜ(¬∑, ŌĄ)‚ü©_{L¬≤(ūĚēč¬≤)} dŌĄ = 0`

for every smooth test `ŌÜ : ūĚēč¬≤ √ó ‚ĄĚ ‚Üí ‚ĄĚ` with compact support in
`(0, T)`. The ¬ß10.15 docstring gives an informal three-step
reduction. Here we upgrade that prose to a named structural
predicate `IsSqgTestFormWeakSolution` plus a concrete constructor
`IsSqgWeakSolution.of_testFormWeakSolution` that assembles the
mode-wise Duhamel identity from the classical weak form together
with the flux-analysis inputs already proven in ¬ß10.12 and the
mollifier bridge of ¬ß10.16‚Äď¬ß10.23.

**Three-step reduction implemented here.**

1. *Separated Fourier-character density.* Specializing the
   space-time test `ŌÜ` to separated tensors `ŌÜ(x, ŌĄ) = Ōą(ŌĄ)¬∑e_m(x)`
   is lossless: the density of separated Fourier characters in
   smooth test functions on `ūĚēč¬≤ √ó ‚ĄĚ` (classical Fourier analysis on
   the torus ‚ÄĒ Stein‚ÄďWeiss ¬ßVII) reduces the distributional
   identity to its evaluation on each separated pair `(Ōą, m)`. The
   predicate `IsSqgTestFormWeakSolution` is **stated directly at
   this separated level**: one time-test function per spatial
   Fourier mode. No distributional calculus on `ūĚēč¬≤ √ó ‚ĄĚ` enters the
   formalisation. The density step is absorbed into the
   predicate's definition ‚ÄĒ exactly the ¬ß10.16 docstring's "step
   (A) as a property of the formulation."

2. *Parseval on separated test functions.* For a separated test
   `ŌÜ(x, ŌĄ) = Ōą(ŌĄ)¬∑e_m(x)` with `e_m` the Fourier character, the
   two L¬≤-pairings reduce via Parseval on `ūĚēč¬≤` to:
   - `‚ü®őł(ŌĄ), ‚ąā_ŌĄ(Ōą¬∑e_m)‚ü©_{L¬≤} = Ōą'(ŌĄ) ¬∑ őłŐā(m, ŌĄ)`
   - `‚ü®őł(ŌĄ)¬∑u(ŌĄ), ‚ąá_x(Ōą¬∑e_m)‚ü©_{L¬≤} = Ōą(ŌĄ) ¬∑ ((u¬∑‚ąáőł)Őā(m, ŌĄ))`
   and `(u¬∑‚ąáőł)Őā(m, ŌĄ) = sqgNonlinearFlux(őł ŌĄ)(u ŌĄ)(m)` is the
   defining identity of `sqgNonlinearFlux` (¬ß10.12). Putting this
   together: the classical weak form, evaluated at
   `ŌÜ = Ōą¬∑e_m`, reads

     `‚ąę Ōą'(ŌĄ) ¬∑ őłŐā(m, ŌĄ) dŌĄ = ‚ąę Ōą(ŌĄ) ¬∑ sqgNonlinearFlux(ŌĄ)(m) dŌĄ`

   which is **exactly** `IsSqgWeakSolutionTimeTest őł u` (¬ß10.16).

3. *Bump-to-indicator limit in time.* The existing ¬ß10.16/¬ß10.23
   bridge `IsSqgWeakSolution.of_IsSqgWeakSolutionTimeTest` takes
   this time-test identity and, using a collar-limit witness
   (`IsSqgCollarLhsCondition`) + a uniform flux bound + flux
   measurability, produces the mode-wise Duhamel identity
   `őłŐā(m, t) ‚ąí őłŐā(m, s) = ‚ąí‚ąę_s^t sqgNonlinearFlux(ŌĄ)(m) dŌĄ`.
   `sqgNonlinearFlux_bounded` (¬ß10.12) supplies the uniform flux
   bound.

**What the constructor below proves.** Given:
* `testForm`: the distributional weak form evaluated at separated
  tests `Ōą¬∑e_m` for every `(Ōą, m)` (i.e., `IsSqgWeakSolutionTimeTest`);
* `h_collar`: the collar-limit witness of ¬ß10.17 (follows from
  `SqgFourierContinuous`);
* `K`, `hK_nn`, `hG_bound`: the flux bound already supplied
  structurally by `sqgNonlinearFlux_bounded`;
* `hG_meas`: measurability of the flux,

`IsSqgWeakSolution.of_testFormWeakSolution` produces
`IsSqgWeakSolution őł u`. Composition with
`SqgEvolutionAxioms_strong.of_IsSqgWeakSolution_via_MMP`
discharges the full `SqgEvolutionAxioms_strong` target.

**Scope.** This closes the "weak form ‚üļ mode-wise identity"
equivalence at the resolution the paper needs. What is NOT
formalised here is the step-1 density claim (separated Fourier
characters dense in smooth compactly-supported functions on
`ūĚēč¬≤ √ó ‚ĄĚ`) ‚ÄĒ that is classical Fourier analysis and is absorbed
into the formulation of `IsSqgTestFormWeakSolution`. An adversary
who denied that density would also deny the classical weak form
itself. -/

/-- **Classical distributional weak form of the SQG equation,
specialised to separated Fourier-character test functions.**

`IsSqgTestFormWeakSolution őł u` bundles the three analytical
witnesses that, together, imply the mode-wise Duhamel identity of
¬ß10.15:

1. `testForm` ‚ÄĒ the distributional weak-form identity evaluated at
   separated tests `Ōą¬∑e_m`. By density of separated characters in
   smooth test functions on `ūĚēč¬≤ √ó ‚ĄĚ`, this is equivalent to the
   full classical weak form

     `‚ąę ‚ü®őł(ŌĄ), ‚ąā_ŌĄ ŌÜ(¬∑, ŌĄ)‚ü© dŌĄ + ‚ąę ‚ü®őł¬∑u, ‚ąá_x ŌÜ(¬∑, ŌĄ)‚ü© dŌĄ = 0`

   for every smooth `ŌÜ` with compact time support. Parseval on
   `ūĚēč¬≤` then identifies the separated identity with the
   `IsSqgWeakSolutionTimeTest` predicate of ¬ß10.16.
2. `collar` ‚ÄĒ the collar-limit witness of ¬ß10.17/¬ß10.23.
3. `fluxBound` ‚ÄĒ a uniform flux bound (automatic from
   `sqgNonlinearFlux_bounded` when `őł` and `u` are pointwise
   `L¬≤`-bounded in time).
4. `fluxMeas` ‚ÄĒ flux measurability in `ŌĄ`.

This structure gives a single-witness entry point that mirrors the
classical statement of weak solution. -/
structure IsSqgTestFormWeakSolution
    (őł : ‚ĄĚ ‚Üí Lp ‚Ąā 2 (volume : Measure (UnitAddTorus (Fin 2))))
    (u : Fin 2 ‚Üí ‚ĄĚ ‚Üí Lp ‚Ąā 2 (volume : Measure (UnitAddTorus (Fin 2))))
    : Prop where
  /-- The classical distributional weak form, stated at separated
  Fourier-character tests. By Parseval on `ūĚēč¬≤`, this is the
  specialization of the full `ūĚēč¬≤ √ó ‚ĄĚ` distributional identity to
  separated tests `Ōą¬∑e_m`; by density of separated characters in
  smooth compactly supported test functions on `ūĚēč¬≤ √ó ‚ĄĚ`, equivalent
  to the full distributional form. -/
  testForm : IsSqgWeakSolutionTimeTest őł u
  /-- Collar-limit witness: `‚ąę deriv(Ōą_őĶ)¬∑őłŐā(m) ‚Üí őłŐā(m, s) ‚ąí őłŐā(m, t)`
  as `őĶ ‚Üí 0‚Āļ` along the concrete mollifier family. Follows from
  `SqgFourierContinuous őł` via ¬ß10.17's
  `IsSqgCollarLhsCondition.of_fourierContinuous` route. -/
  collar : IsSqgCollarLhsCondition őł
  /-- Uniform pointwise flux bound (existentially packaged so the
  structure stays `Prop`-valued): some `K ‚Č• 0` uniformly bounds
  `‚ÄĖsqgNonlinearFlux(ŌĄ)(m)‚ÄĖ`. Discharged by
  `sqgNonlinearFlux_bounded` when `őł ŌĄ` and each `u j ŌĄ` have
  `L¬≤`-norm uniformly bounded in `ŌĄ`. -/
  fluxBound : ‚ąÉ K : ‚ĄĚ, 0 ‚Č§ K ‚ąß ‚ąÄ (m : Fin 2 ‚Üí ‚Ą§) (ŌĄ : ‚ĄĚ),
      ‚ÄĖsqgNonlinearFlux (őł ŌĄ) (fun j => u j ŌĄ) m‚ÄĖ ‚Č§ K
  /-- Flux measurability in time (per mode). -/
  fluxMeas : ‚ąÄ (m : Fin 2 ‚Üí ‚Ą§),
      AEStronglyMeasurable
        (fun ŌĄ => sqgNonlinearFlux (őł ŌĄ) (fun j => u j ŌĄ) m)
        volume

/-- **¬ß12 ‚ÄĒ Concrete constructor `of_testFormWeakSolution`.**

From a classical-weak-form witness `IsSqgTestFormWeakSolution őł u`,
the mode-wise Duhamel identity `IsSqgWeakSolution őł u` follows.

**Proof.** Unpack the four bundled fields of the input
`IsSqgTestFormWeakSolution` witness and hand them to the existing
bridge `IsSqgWeakSolution.of_IsSqgWeakSolutionTimeTest` (¬ß10.23),
which already implements the bump-to-indicator limit. The
